    summary: 'When the disbelievers plotted to kill Isa, Allah saved him by raising him up to Himself. The Quran declares with absolute certainty: "They did not kill him, nor did they crucify him." Isa remains alive in the heavens and will return before the Day of Judgment as a sign of the Hour, to establish justice and affirm the truth of Islam.',
    order: 6,
    paragraphs: [
      {
        id: 'isa-ch06-p01',
        text: 'The end of Isa\'s earthly mission was as miraculous as its beginning. When the disbelievers among the Children of Israel plotted to seize and kill him, Allah intervened directly. The Quran addresses one of the most consequential claims in religious history with definitive clarity: "And their saying, \'Indeed, we have killed the Messiah, Isa, the son of Maryam, the messenger of Allah.\' And they did not kill him, nor did they crucify him; but [another] was made to resemble him to them. And indeed, those who differ over it are in doubt about it. They have no knowledge of it except the following of assumption. And they did not kill him, for certain. Rather, Allah raised him to Himself. And ever is Allah Exalted in Might and Wise." This verse is one of the clearest statements in the Quran. The crucifixion that others claim happened to Isa was an illusion — someone else was made to look like him and was crucified in his place, while Allah raised Isa alive to the heavens. Ibn Kathir records multiple narrations explaining that Allah cast the likeness of Isa upon another person — some say a volunteer from among the disciples, others say a traitor who had betrayed Isa — and this person was crucified while Isa was raised. The Quran further confirms: "O Isa, indeed I will take you and raise you to Myself and purify you from those who disbelieve and make those who follow you superior to those who disbelieve until the Day of Resurrection." This promise was fulfilled — Isa was saved, raised, and his true followers were given dignity until the end of time.',
        phase: 'quran',
